  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "The law of inertia, also known as Newton's First Law of Motion, states that an object will remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by an external force. It's important to note that the law of inertia itself doesn't quantify the magnitude of any force; rather, it describes the tendency of objects to resist changes in their state of motion.\n\nIf you are looking to find the magnitude of a force applied to an object, you would need additional information about the mass of the object and the acceleration caused by the force, as described by Newton's Second Law of Motion. According to this second law, the force applied to an object is given by \\( F = m \\cdot a \\), where:\n\n- \\( F \\) is the force,\n- \\( m \\) is the mass of the object, and\n- \\( a \\) is the acceleration of the object.\n\nIn summary, the law of inertia does not provide a method to calculate the magnitude of a force, as it focuses on the behavior of objects in the absence of net external forces. For calculations involving force magnitude, you should refer to Newton's Second Law.",
